XML_CASESUMMARY.SUMMARY:
This single-vehicle collision occurred around dawn on a weekend morning. The crash occurred on a straight, level stretch of a five-lane, two-way bituminous roadway, running northwest and southeast. Traffic lanes in both directions are bordered on the outside by bicycle lanes, which are bordered by parking lanes at the curbs. The posted speed limit in the area of the crash is 72 kmph (45 mph). At the time of the crash, there were no adverse weather conditions, and the roadway was free of defects.
Vehicle one (V1), a 2000 Chevrolet C-3500 4X4 pickup, was being towed by another vehicle of unknown make and model. V1 was attached by a non-fixed linkage (rope), and was unoccupied at the time of the crash. V1 broke loose and departed the road to the right side, where its right front wheel and axle were damaged. V1 impacted a fire hydrant with its front plane and came to rest partially on the sidewalk.
V1 was a stolen vehicle that had been stripped. The towing vehicle fled the scene, unidentified. No interview data could be obtained. The critical precrash event was coded: This vehicle control loss due to/ Non-disabling vehicle problem (specified as: Tow rope broke (non-fixed linkage) & V1 became detached from the tow unit. Unoccupied V1 was placed in motion). The critical reason for the event was attributed to V1, and was coded as a vehicle related factor: Tow rope broke (non-fixed linkage). If a driver was present then that person may have been able to drive the vehicle to a controlled stop before departing the roadway. Without the presence of a driver there was no control over the vehicle.
